        <body>
            <head>13. Notes of a <orgName corresp="recft7WGb7Fww0wma">National Security
                    Council</orgName> Meeting<note n="1" place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d13fn1"
                    >Source: <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">Ronald Reagan</persName> Library,
                    Executive Secretariat, <gloss target="#t_NSC_1"><orgName
                            corresp="recft7WGb7Fww0wma">NSC</orgName></gloss> Meeting Files,
                    NSC00049 05/03/1982 [<gloss target="#t_START_1"><rs corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O"
                            type="event">START</rs></gloss>]. Top Secret. Drafted by <persName
                        corresp="recaUAEdm9DKpE2cm">Wheeler</persName>. Brackets and ellipses are in
                    the original. The original text is handwritten. The editor transcribed the
                    portion of the text here specifically for this volume. An image of the note is
                    Appendix A. According to <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">the
                        President</persName>’s Daily Diary, the meeting took place in the Cabinet
                    Room and ended at 10:52 a.m. No formal minutes of this meeting were
                    found.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1982-05-03T09:45:00-04:00">May 3, 1982, 9:45 a.m.</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <p>[<orgName corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">State</orgName> absent when <persName
                    corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">President</persName> arrives]</p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">Pres:</hi> tells stories . . . $120 tickets—12,000
                pennies</p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">Judge <persName corresp="rec5nWAotd8wedNxI"
                        >Clark</persName>:</hi> units of account &amp; insert to be discussed
                today—hold on <rs corresp="recvMEtDFpnXkyj45" type="topic">verification</rs>—90%
                agreement . . . do we limit <gloss target="#t_TW_1"><rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF"
                        type="topic">TW</rs></gloss> directly or indirectly—<persName
                    corresp="rec2p5eZ5kgeXCRJ4">Bud McF</persName> will review charts<note n="2"
                    place="foot" xml:id="d13fn2">Not attached.</note>
            </p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">
                    <persName corresp="rec2p5eZ5kgeXCRJ4">Bud McFarlane</persName>:</hi> criteria =
                (1) carry out strategy (2) deep cuts (3) equality (4) easily understanding (5)
                satisfy <rs corresp="recydYSQ1GmGAh8yu" type="compound-subject">allies</rs> (6)
                allow for stability—all agree (1) substantial difference from <gloss
                    target="#t_SALT_1"><rs corresp="rec6OIA4luUvtBKNn" type="event"
                    >SALT</rs></gloss> II (2) 5000 <rs corresp="rechpv4Wz0TdKArbg" type="topic"
                    >warheads</rs> (3) focus on <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1"><rs
                        corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBM</rs></gloss> (4) treat <rs
                    corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE" type="topic">bombers</rs> differently . . .
                ultimately 250 on each side (5) limit <gloss target="#t_TW_1"><rs
                        corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic">TW</rs></gloss>, but how
                    ??—<orgName corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">STATE</orgName> &amp; <gloss
                    target="#t_JCS_1"><orgName corresp="recYt5V8hImTp3Aah">JCS</orgName></gloss> . .
                . 5000 W/H → substantial cut in <gloss target="#t_TW_1"><rs
                        corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic">TW</rs></gloss> (down to 2–3 M
                kg)—easily understandable, deep reductions—cons w/<gloss target="#t_WH_1">WH</gloss>
                = breakout (even w/only modest <gloss target="#t_TW_1"><rs
                        corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic">TW</rs></gloss> advantage) . . .
                penaids . . . accuracy or yield advantage—cons w/ <gloss target="#t_TW_1"><rs
                        corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic">TW</rs></gloss> = understandability
                . . . verifiability . . . Soviets alone called to reduce to 2M (we’d increase) . . .
                Soviets may also wish to limit bomber P/L</p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">Adm <persName corresp="recWMTuTWgI0GTsmw"
                        >Inman</persName>:</hi> cannot give certainty w/o <rs
                    corresp="reclbsHvbXLer8sMP" type="topic">onsite inspection</rs>, but can give
                high confidence—(reviews factors that allows high confidence)—moderate-to-high w/
                mobile <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1"><rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic"
                        >ICBMs</rs></gloss>, high w/ fixed, for <rs corresp="rechpv4Wz0TdKArbg"
                    type="topic">W/Hs</rs> . . . (review other measures)</p>
            <table>
                <row>
                    <cell rendition="#bottom #nopad">high = &lt;10%</cell>
                    <cell role="brace" rows="2">}</cell>
                    <cell rendition="#middle" rows="2">
                        <hi rendition="simple_italic">confidence</hi>
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell rendition="#top #nopad">moderate = 25–50%</cell>
                </row>
            </table>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">Judge <persName corresp="rec5nWAotd8wedNxI"
                        >Clark</persName>:</hi> roundtable discussion</p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">
                    <persName corresp="receeGTv8IaT6tukJ">Haig</persName>:</hi> (praise Bud’s
                summary) . . . must focus on both military <hi rendition="simple_italic">and</hi>
                political aspects . . . all agree on <gloss target="#t_BM_1"><rs
                        corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04" type="topic">BM</rs></gloss> 5000 <rs
                    corresp="rechpv4Wz0TdKArbg" type="topic">W/Hs</rs> (= ¹/3 <rs
                    corresp="recHoFOsQcM4e5M4k" type="topic">reduction</rs> from current levels—no
                more than half could be <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1"><rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P"
                        type="topic">ICBM</rs></gloss>
                <rs corresp="rechpv4Wz0TdKArbg" type="topic">W/Hs</rs>—require Soviets to do 60% <rs
                    corresp="recHoFOsQcM4e5M4k" type="topic">reduction</rs> in their best systems)—3
                major problems w/ <gloss target="#t_TW_1"><rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF"
                        type="topic">TW</rs></gloss>: (1) <gloss target="#t_TW_1"><rs
                        corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic">TW</rs></gloss> above current
                levels . . . 1.3 to 2 . . . paper equivalence but real disparity (2) 65% cut for
                Soviets in <gloss target="#t_TW_1"><rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic"
                        >TW</rs></gloss> . . . not credible (3) hard to verify <gloss
                    target="#t_TW_1"><rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic">TW</rs></gloss> .
                . . 1M kg uncertainty equivalent to 180 <rs corresp="recAug8nb5QfVfzky" type="topic"
                    >SS–18s</rs>—ceiling of 850 missiles is most significant guard against
                breakout—go beyond satellites for <rs corresp="recvMEtDFpnXkyj45" type="topic"
                    >verification</rs>, <hi rendition="simple_italic">but</hi> wait on decision <hi
                    rendition="simple_italic">after</hi> fix position</p>
            <pb facs="0071" n="42" xml:id="pg_42"/>
            <p>5000/2500</p>
            <p>850/250</p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic"><persName corresp="recg0WDsRQgtuIKMw"
                        >Weinberger</persName>:</hi> vital disagreement (passes out chart)<note
                    n="3" place="foot" xml:id="d13fn3">Not attached.</note>—if we just limit <rs
                    corresp="rechpv4Wz0TdKArbg" type="topic">warheads</rs>, we’d play into hands of
                Kennedy &amp; Hatfield—not the relevant measure, since yield is the real measure,
                and one gets at yield through <gloss target="#t_TW_1"><rs
                        corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic">TW</rs></gloss>—it can be easily
                understood—not relevant that Soviets wouldn’t like proposal . . . (analogy to) what
                Soviets are doing at <gloss target="#t_INF_1"><rs corresp="recgLCwFE47waxYP9"
                        type="event">INF</rs></gloss> now—<rs corresp="recvMEtDFpnXkyj45"
                    type="topic">verification</rs> uncertainties affect every proposal—*speech
                should be specific</p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">
                    <persName corresp="rec4pU3LOkVX0BKPW">Hayward</persName>:</hi> should I discuss
                certification <hi rendition="simple_italic">and</hi> position? (A = . . . do both .
                . .)—<rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic">T/W</rs> important, but <gloss
                    target="#t_JCS_1"><orgName corresp="recYt5V8hImTp3Aah">JCS</orgName></gloss>
                think we should get at it indirectly . . . combination of (2500 <gloss
                    target="#t_ICBM_1"><rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic"
                    >ICBM</rs></gloss> ? or 5000 <gloss target="#t_BM_1"><rs
                        corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04" type="topic">BM</rs></gloss>) <rs
                    corresp="rechpv4Wz0TdKArbg" type="topic">W/Hs</rs> &amp; 850 missiles gets our
                big cut—if you take <rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic">T/W</rs> as
                principal indicator, you’ll end up less . . . we’ll end up w/ imbalance in <rs
                    corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic">T/W</rs>, no matter what our position
                is</p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic"><persName corresp="recM8U5HOaBRfTDmg"
                        >Rostow</persName>:</hi> important difference in principle remains—recommend
                in speeches you talk about # of <rs corresp="rechpv4Wz0TdKArbg" type="topic"
                    >warheads</rs> and their destructive capacity, w/o going into detail on how we
                measure that—we essentially agree w/<gloss target="#t_OSD_1"><orgName
                        corresp="recoMngX7uLPacWDx">OSD</orgName></gloss> position . . . (refer to
                Chart) (slight confusion as people shuffle paper) . . . most fundamental objection
                to <orgName corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">State</orgName>/<gloss target="#t_JCS_1"
                        ><orgName corresp="recYt5V8hImTp3Aah">JCS</orgName></gloss> position is that
                it would be profoundly destabilizing (fewer aimpoints would encourage larger <rs
                    corresp="rechpv4Wz0TdKArbg" type="topic">warheads</rs>) . . . press in direction
                of smaller <rs corresp="rechpv4Wz0TdKArbg" type="topic">warheads</rs>, which would
                decrease attractiveness of 1st strike—Committee on the Present Danger’s experience
                was that people had strong views on reaching agreement, but did not understand
                details . . . that’s not the function of the American people—cites (—?) that Soviets
                prepared to negotiate on <rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic">T/W</rs>—my
                former memo was that unless we restore . . . —<gloss target="#t_START_1"><rs
                        corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O" type="event">START</rs></gloss> &amp; <gloss
                    target="#t_INF_1"><rs corresp="recgLCwFE47waxYP9" type="event">INF</rs></gloss>
                are <hi rendition="simple_italic">not</hi> the centerpiece of our <rs
                    corresp="rectqbCKMJaN5yPfG" type="topic">foreign policy</rs>—Soviets will have
                no motivation to enter into agreement unless we convince<note n="4" place="foot"
                    xml:id="d13fn4">One line was cut off in the copy of this document in the
                    file.</note> course carries substantial risk—we haven’t solved the <gloss
                    target="#t_MX_1"><rs corresp="rec99k2btquR4fVXS" type="topic">MX</rs></gloss>
                problem, established a strong mil presence SWA, etc.—we’re all recommending the same
                goal of equal <rs corresp="recMrVNgNJpQ8DjcR" type="topic">deterrence</rs></p>
            <p>(<persName corresp="rect6NyHqNFnrOJ42">Jean Kirkpatrick</persName> leaves)</p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">Gen <persName corresp="recCAUUmNdxvAWExm"
                        >Rowny</persName>:</hi> are the goals understandable &amp; can we
                    negotiate?—<hi rendition="simple_italic">my</hi> preference is that we set goals
                and then phase—are goals plausible? . . . set goals, then do the “possible”
                first—will they come down? . . . we’re giving up <gloss target="#t_SLBM_1"><rs
                        corresp="recnGcR0g6J7yKHTE" type="topic">SLBMs</rs></gloss> later on . . .
                they fear <rs corresp="recbgJJiOGydQB0ct" type="topic">D–5</rs> . . . we give up
                something in long run, ask them to give up something in the short run</p>
            <pb facs="0072" n="43" xml:id="pg_43"/>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">Judge <persName corresp="rec5nWAotd8wedNxI"
                        >Clark</persName>:</hi> evidence is in for your later decision—move to
                    <gloss target="#t_START_1"><rs corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O" type="event"
                        >START</rs></gloss> insert for May 9th<note n="5" place="foot"
                    xml:id="d13fn5">See <ref target="#d11fn5">footnote 5, Document 11</ref>.</note>
            </p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic"><persName corresp="recg0WDsRQgtuIKMw"
                        >Weinberger</persName>:</hi> 3 quick points—U.S. cut vs. add to get to
                parity—Soviets did negotiate in <gloss target="#t_INF_1"><rs
                        corresp="recgLCwFE47waxYP9" type="event">INF</rs></gloss> where only they
                cut</p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">Judge <persName corresp="rec5nWAotd8wedNxI"
                        >Clark</persName>:</hi> insert . . . comments?</p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic"><persName corresp="recM8U5HOaBRfTDmg"
                        >Rostow</persName>:</hi> add consultation w/ Cong’l leaders (. . . to <rs
                    corresp="recydYSQ1GmGAh8yu" type="compound-subject">allies</rs>)</p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic"><persName corresp="recg0WDsRQgtuIKMw"
                        >Weinberger</persName>:</hi> add <rs corresp="reclbsHvbXLer8sMP"
                    type="topic">onsite</rs>
                <rs corresp="recvMEtDFpnXkyj45" type="topic">verification</rs></p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">
                    <persName corresp="receeGTv8IaT6tukJ">Haig</persName>:</hi> disagree . . . not
                before we agree on what to verify</p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic"><persName corresp="recM8U5HOaBRfTDmg"
                        >Rostow</persName>:</hi> save <rs corresp="recvMEtDFpnXkyj45" type="topic"
                    >verification</rs> for later speech</p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">
                    <persName corresp="rec4pU3LOkVX0BKPW">Hayward</persName>:</hi>
                <orgName corresp="recYt5V8hImTp3Aah">Chiefs</orgName> don’t have issue that onsite
                should be in or out of speech . . . more worried select choice where only onsite
                would work</p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic"><persName corresp="recEQQb67MTNPG0x8"
                    >Baker</persName>:</hi> are we checking on prior statements by Pres <persName
                    corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">Reagan</persName> re: <rs
                    corresp="recvMEtDFpnXkyj45" type="topic">verification</rs>, etc.</p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">
                    <persName corresp="recWMTuTWgI0GTsmw">Inman</persName>:</hi> sooner or later
                you’ll have to decide what degree of confidence you want</p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">
                    <persName corresp="receeGTv8IaT6tukJ">Haig</persName>:</hi> you’re faced
                w/sharply divergent views—campaign statement for longterm goal excellent (don’t pose
                threat to one another)—add to that now that we’ll proceed over time to that
                goal—taking 2500 <rs corresp="rechpv4Wz0TdKArbg" type="topic">warheads</rs> away
                will drive them to smaller missiles—put equal <rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF"
                    type="topic">T/W</rs> forth at a <hi rendition="simple_italic">later</hi>
                stage—capture essence of both positions but in a more realistic way—Soviets won’t
                negotiate <rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic">T/W</rs></p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic"><persName corresp="recg0WDsRQgtuIKMw"
                        >Weinberger</persName>:</hi> on phased approach, comment that comes to mind
                is that in long run all will be dead—Soviets will negotiate <gloss target="#t_TW_1"
                        ><rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic">TW</rs></gloss>
            </p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">Judge <persName corresp="rec5nWAotd8wedNxI"
                        >Clark</persName>:</hi> (cites Gelb article of yesterday . . . rendition of
                16 Apr 16 mtg. <hi rendition="simple_italic">et al</hi>)<note n="6" place="foot"
                    xml:id="d13fn6">Reference is to Leslie H. Gelb, “U.S. Forging a New Concept For
                    Curbing Strategic Arms,” <hi rendition="simple_italic"><rs
                            corresp="recYdozPXa32MjJBK" type="work">New York Times</rs></hi>, May 2,
                    1982, p. 1.</note>—compulsion to give argument to press a mystery to me</p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic"><persName corresp="recM8U5HOaBRfTDmg"
                        >Rostow</persName>:</hi> another mtg?</p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">
                    <persName corresp="rec5nWAotd8wedNxI">Clark</persName>:</hi> yes, on interim
                measures, after Pres. decides.</p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">Pres:</hi> if <rs corresp="rechpv4Wz0TdKArbg"
                    type="topic">W/Hs</rs>, do you not automatically achieve ↓ <gloss
                    target="#t_TW_1"><rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic">TW</rs></gloss>?
                    (<persName corresp="receeGTv8IaT6tukJ">Haig</persName>: almost same—<persName
                    corresp="recg0WDsRQgtuIKMw">Weinberger</persName>: no—<persName
                    corresp="recM8U5HOaBRfTDmg">Rostow</persName>: no . . . <persName
                    corresp="receeGTv8IaT6tukJ">Haig</persName>: require they do all, we do
                nothing—Wein.: <gloss target="#t_INF_1"><rs corresp="recgLCwFE47waxYP9" type="event"
                        >INF</rs></gloss> . . . never get them to table)</p>
        </body>
